      <!-- ─── Why Script Instead of Mod? ─────────────────────────────── -->
      <section id="why-lua" class="why-lua section-pad">
        <div class="container">
          <h2 class="section-title">Why Script Instead of Writing a Mod?</h2>
          <p class="section-subtitle">
            Server owners iterate faster, players see the result live.
          </p>
          <div class="why-lua-grid">
            <div class="why-card">
              <div class="why-icon">⚡</div>
              <h3>Reload Scripts Instantly</h3>
              <p>Edit a file, run <code>/pxignis reload</code>. Changes are live in milliseconds — no server restart, no reconnecting players.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="why-card">
              <div class="why-icon">🚫</div>
              <h3>No Recompilation</h3>
              <p>Skip the Java toolchain. No Gradle, no Loom, no 5-minute build cycles. Just a text editor and a save.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="why-card">
              <div class="why-icon">🛡️</div>
              <h3>Safer Iteration</h3>
              <p>Lua errors are isolated per-script. One bad handler doesn't take down the whole server — and rollback is just <code>git checkout</code>.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="why-card">
              <div class="why-icon">🤝</div>
              <h3>Server Owners Customize Gameplay</h3>
              <p>Hand the scripts folder to a community manager. They can tune shops, classes, and events without ever touching Java.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="why-card">
              <div class="why-icon">📦</div>
              <h3>No IDE Required</h3>
              <p>VS Code, Notepad++, vim — anything that saves <code>.lua</code> works. The runtime reads files directly from disk.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="why-card">
              <div class="why-icon">🔌</div>
              <h3>Full Fabric Power</h3>
              <p>Lua wraps the entire Fabric API surface. You get events, networking, world data — without writing a single Java class.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

